<br>  Hello Bhaskar Chowdhury,<br>

Today I'll show you how you can copy lines without moving your
cursor.
So I was working on some Janky module, and I had this piece of
code:

5 file '/etc/init.d/janky',
4 source =3D> 'files/etc/init.d/janky',

3 owner =3D> 'root',

2 group =3D> 'root',

1 mode =3D> 755;

44 =E2=96=88

My cursor positioned on line 44. I needed a similar block, with
one difference - "conf.d" instead of "init.d". So, I would copy
the block above, and make the change.

Now, in these kind of situations, most of the people would
usually visually select the wanted lines and copy them. That's
fine.

But, there is another handy (and sometimes faster) way to perform
these kinds of operations.

All I had to run was: -5,t.

and the result was:

11 file '/etc/init.d/janky',
10 source =3D> 'files/etc/init.d/janky',
9 owner =3D> 'root',
8 group =3D> 'root',
7 mode =3D> 755;
6

5 file '/etc/init.d/janky',

4 source =3D> 'files/etc/init.d/janky',

3 owner =3D> 'root',

2 group =3D> 'root',

1 mode =3D> 755;
50 =E2=96=88

I got exactly what I wanted, and I could proceed with editing the
second block.

Now, let's explain the command... :t is an alias of the co[py]
command.
As I use relative line numbers, I saw the block I wanted to copy
starts at 5 lines above my cursor, so that's -5.

So -5,t. is the same as -5,co.

We can read these as "copy everything from 5 lines above the
cursor, up to current cursor line, and paste it".

More about co[py] in next issue!

Cheers,
Jovica

P.S. We have a new buddy in Vim community, Giorgio ;)

